Start with a sketch. Leftward numbers (toward \(-\infty\)) will be less than our boundary \(z\), so we shade a left region with area 0.27.


You should go to your \(z\)-table and find the \(z\)-score with the left area closest to 0.27.

\(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
-0.64 0.2611
-0.63 0.2643
-0.62 0.2676
-0.61 0.2709
-0.6 0.2743
-0.59 0.2776

It turns out the exact answer is \(z=-0.612813\), which could be found by using an inverse normal function. On a spreadsheet:

=Norm.Inv(0.27,0,1)

Using R:

qnorm(0.27)

But, the \(z\)-table is accurate enough, so I will accept either -0.62 or -0.61 (anything within 0.01 of -0.612813).

You might find it helpful to visualize with a spinner.
